\n","- Standard class libraries\n","- Tools like `javadoc`\n","\n","**JRE** (Java Runtime Environment) is what you need only to *run* Java programs. It lacks the compiler and some development tools.\n","\n","### Why We Need the JDK?\n","- We’re writing code, compiling it, generating documentation, and running tests (e.g., JUnit).  \n","- The JRE alone is not enough for development since it doesn’t include the compiler.\n","\n","**Download Link**: [https://www.oracle.com/java/technologies/downloads/#java21](https://www.oracle.com/java/technologies/downloads/#java21)  \n","\n","**Steps**:\n","1. Choose the LTS version (e.g., Java 21).\n","2. Download the appropriate installer for your operating system (Windows `.exe`, macOS `.dmg`, Linux `.rpm` or `.deb`, etc.).  \n","3. Run the installer.  \n","\n","---\n","\n","**Exercise**:\n","1. **Download and install** the latest JDK on your machine if you haven’t yet.  \n","\n","---\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"eXPYhJES6kbe"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# **4. Coding Conventions**\n","\n","Coding conventions are important because they:\n","- Make code more readable and maintainable.\n","- Provide a standard style that multiple developers can follow.\n","- Reduce confusion when reading or reviewing code from different authors.\n","\n","---"],"metadata":{"id":"RJzcn8kdvoi1"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["\n","## 4.1 Oracle Java Coding Conventions\n","\n","Reference:  \n","[https://www.oracle.com/java/technologies/javase/codeconventions-contents.html](https://www.oracle.com/java/technologies/javase/codeconventions-contents.html)\n","\n","Focus on:\n","- **Section 9**: Naming conventions (for classes, methods, variables, constants, etc.).  \n","\n","### Example of Code *Following* Conventions\n","\n","- Class name starts with uppercase `HelloWorld`.\n","- Variables use camelCase, constants use ALL_CAPS, etc.\n","\n","### Example of Code *Not* Following Conventions\n","\n","- Class name all lowercase, or “testclass”.\n","- Braces aligned incorrectly, inconsistent indentation, etc.\n","\n","Below is a short code snippet demonstrating *good* vs. *poor* convention usage side by side.\n","\n","```java\n","/**\n"," * GoodConventionExample class\n"," * Demonstrates correct naming and formatting based on Oracle Java coding conventions.\n"," */\n","public class GoodConventionExample {\n","    \n","    private static final int MAX_COUNT = 10;\n","    \n","    public static void main(String[] args) {\n","        for (int i = 0; i < MAX_COUNT; i++) {\n","            System.out.println(\"Count: \" + i);\n","        }\n","    }\n","}\n","```\n","\n","```java\n","// This code deliberately breaks typical style conventions\n","public class poorconventionexample{\n","    public static final int Max_Count=10;\n","    public static void main(String[] ARGS){\n","    for(int I=0;I<Max_Count;I++){\n","    System.out.println(\"count:\"+I);}\n","    }\n","}\n","```\n","\n","---\n","\n","**Exercise**:  \n","1. Look at this [repo](https://github.com/gephi/gephi) and discuss whether it follows these conventions.  \n","2. Find on GitHub:\n","   - One project that **strictly follows** Oracle Java coding conventions.\n","   - One project that **does not** follow (or partially follows) them.\n","3. Fix the following examples below to follow good conventions."],"metadata":{"id":"Kq50bJP--VVM"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["%%writefile ConventionExample1.java\n","package example.hello;\n","\n","import java.util.Scanner;\n","\n","/**\n"," * This is a simple HelloWorld program.\n"," */\n","public class HelloWorld {\n","\n","    /**\n","     * Main method to start the application.\n","     */\n","    public static void main(String[] args) {\n","        Greetingservice greetingService = new Greetingservice();\n","        greetingService.greet_console();\n","        greetingService.Farewell();\n","    }\n","}\n","\n","/**\n"," * This class provides greeting services.\n"," */\n","class Greetingservice {\n","\n","    /**\n","     * Prints a greeting message to the console.\n","     */\n","    public void greet_console() {\n","        System.out.println(\"Hello, World! Welcome to Java Programming.\");\n","    }\n","\n","    /**\n","     * Prints a farewell message to the console.\n","     */\n","    public void Farewell() {\n","        System.out.println(\"Goodbye! Have a great day!\");\n","    }\n","}"],"metadata":{"id":"CB7YRwCm5c3Q","colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1737472937536,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":136,"user":{"displayName":"Tyler","userId":"06315977947093285888"}},"outputId":"10c085dc-47d0-491b-b549-e9d87666cca0"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Writing ConventionExample1.java\n"]}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["%%writefile ConventionExample2.java\n","package com.example.shapes;\n","\n","/**\n"," * This class demonstrates calculating properties of a circle.\n"," */\n","public class CircleCalculator {\n","\n","    /**\n","     * Approximate value of Pi.\n","     */\n","    private static final double pi = 3.14159;\n","\n","    /**\n","     * Calculates the circumference of a circle given its radius.\n","     */\n","    public double calculateCircumference(double radius) {\n","        return 2 * pi * radius;\n","    }\n","\n","    /**\n","     * Calculates the area of a circle given its radius.\n","     */\n","    public double calculateArea(double radius) {\n","        return pi * radius * radius;\n","    }\n","\n","    /**\n","     * Main method to demonstrate circle calculations.\n","     */\n","    public static void main(String[] args) {\n","        CircleCalculator calculator = new CircleCalculator();\n","\n","        double r = 5.0; // Local variable for the radius of the circle\n","\n","        // Calculating properties\n","        double C = calculator.calculateCircumference(r);\n","        double A = calculator.calculateArea(r);\n","\n","        // Output the results\n","        System.out.println(\"For a circle with radius \" + r + \":\");\n","        System.out.println(\"Circumference: \" + C);\n","        System.out.println(\"Area: \" + A);\n","    }\n","}"],"metadata":{"id":"QgO4623f8EpT"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Check your answers below:**"],"metadata":{"id":"CZcRWHeDiqv0"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["!wget -qO- https://tylerchan.me/temp/ConventionExample1Answer.java | tr -d '\\r' > ConventionExample1Answer.java\n","!wget -qO- https://tylerchan.me/temp/ConventionExample2Answer.java | tr -d '\\r' > ConventionExample2Answer.java\n","compare(\"ConventionExample1Answer.java\", \"ConventionExample1.java\")\n","print()\n","compare(\"ConventionExample2Answer.java\", \"ConventionExample2.java\")"],"metadata":{"id":"0b2Jf2Cd65iJ"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["---\n","\n","# **5. Offline Java Documentation**\n","\n","**Oracle** provides official documentation for the standard Java API. You can view it online or download it to read offline.\n","\n","1. On the [JDK download page](https://www.oracle.com/java/technologies/downloads/#java21), look for the **\"Documentation Download\"** button.\n","2. Download the documentation `.zip` file.\n","3. Unzip it to a folder of your choice.\n","4. Open `index.html` in a web browser to explore the offline docs."],"metadata":{"id":"EQ89gWvoFHg4"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["![javadoc.png](data:image/png;base64,)"],"metadata":{"id":"U0UjFG8pFItM"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Observation**:  \n","- This offline documentation is generated using the **javadoc** tool, the same tool we’ve been discussing.  \n","- You’ll find all standard classes (e.g., `String`, `List`, `Map`) with the same content as on [docs.oracle.com](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/).\n","\n","### Example: Inspecting the `String` Class\n","\n","1. In your offline docs folder, navigate to **`java.base/java/lang/String.html`** (the path might vary slightly, but it usually follows the package structure).  \n","2. Open `String.html` in a browser.  \n","3. Notice the fields (e.g., `private final byte[] value;`) and methods (`startsWith()`, `equals()`, etc.).  \n","4. Observe how each method has documentation (description, parameters, return types, etc.)—all are javadoc comments embedded in the source code.\n","\n","---\n","\n","## `src.zip` in the JDK\n","\n","When you install the JDK, it places a file called **`src.zip`** in the `lib/` directory (or a similarly named directory depending on your OS). This ZIP file contains **all the source code** for the Java standard library.\n","\n","### Exploring `src.zip`\n","\n","1. Go to your JDK installation folder. Typically on:\n","   - **Windows**: `C:\\Program Files\\Java\\jdk-<version>\\lib\\src.zip`\n","   - **macOS**: `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/jdk-<version>.jdk/Contents/Home/lib/src.zip`\n","   - **Linux**: `/usr/lib/jvm/<version>/lib/src.zip` (or similar)\n","2. Unzip `src.zip` (copy it elsewhere first if needed).\n","3. Open the extracted files. You’ll see the **package hierarchy**: `java/base/java/lang/`, `java/util/`, etc.\n","\n","### Inspecting the `String` Class Source\n","\n","- Inside `java/lang/`, find **`String.java`**.  \n","- Open it in an editor or IDE.  \n","- Look for the same fields and methods you saw in the offline documentation (`private final byte[] value;`, `startsWith()`, `equals()`, etc.).\n","\n","#### Observe the Javadoc and Coding Conventions\n","\n","- You’ll see **javadoc comments** for each class and method, just like in the HTML docs.\n","- Notice how it **follows the Oracle Java Coding Conventions**:\n","  - Class name `String` is capitalized.\n","  - Private fields are typically `lowerCamelCase`.\n","  - Constants (if any) would be in `UPPER_CASE`.\n","  - Indentation and brace style are consistent.\n","\n","**Discussion**:  \n","- Compare Oracle’s official source code to the [Oracle Java Coding Conventions](https://www.oracle.com/java/technologies/javase/codeconventions-contents.html).  \n","- Notice that even minor details (like bracket placement, spacing, indentation) are consistent.\n","\n","---\n","\n","**Exercise**\n","1. **Download the Java docs** zip file. Unzip and open `index.html`.  \n","3. Navigate to **`java.base/java/lang/String.html`** and find `startsWith()` or `equals()`.  \n","4. **Unpack `src.zip`**. Locate `String.java` in `java/lang/`.  \n","5. Compare the javadoc in `String.java` to the offline docs you just opened.  \n","6. Identify at least two coding conventions you see in the `String` source code (e.g., indentation style, naming, brace placement).  \n","7. Discuss how closely the JDK source code follows the official [Oracle conventions](https://www.oracle.com/java/technologies/javase/codeconventions-contents.html).\n","\n","---"],"metadata":{"id":"YGrV_g8d8HwC"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# **6. Javadoc**\n","\n","Javadoc is a tool that generates API documentation from comments in your code. We use special tags (e.g., `@author`, `@version`, `@param`, `@return`, `@exception`, `@see`, `@since`, `@deprecated`) to describe various elements.\n","\n","See this link for some tutorials from Oracle:\n","[https://www.oracle.com/technical-resources/articles/java/javadoc-tool.html](https://www.oracle.com/technical-resources/articles/java/javadoc-tool.html)\n","\n","**Key points**:\n","- By default, Javadoc excludes `private` members.\n","- You can include them with the `-private` flag or in Eclipse by checking “private” in the Javadoc generation wizard.\n","\n","---"],"metadata":{"id":"y1z73Q1GxPIQ"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## 6.1 Example Code with Javadoc Tags\n","\n","The following code uses all major tags. We’ll also show how to generate the documentation afterward."],"metadata":{"id":"efMXMgaT9KlO"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["%%writefile JavadocExample.java\n","/**\n"," * <h1>JavadocExample</h1>\n"," * A simple class to demonstrate Javadoc tags in Java.\n"," *\n"," * @author YourName\n"," * @version 1.0\n"," * @since 1.0\n"," * @see java.lang.String\n"," */\n","public class JavadocExample {\n","\n","    /**\n","     * Adds two numbers together.\n","     *\n","     * @param a the first number\n","     * @param b the second number\n","     * @return the sum of {@code a} and {@code b}\n","     * @exception IllegalArgumentException if a or b is negative\n","     * @deprecated This method is just an example; use Math.addExact(a, b) instead\n","     */\n","    @Deprecated\n","    public int addNumbers(int a, int b) {\n","        if (a < 0 || b < 0) {\n","            throw new IllegalArgumentException(\"Numbers must be non-negative.\");\n","        }\n","        return a + b;\n","    }\n","\n","    /**\n","     * Main method, not very interesting.\n","     */\n","    public static void main(String[] args) {\n","        JavadocExample example = new JavadocExample();\n","        System.out.println(\"3 + 4 = \" + example.addNumbers(3,4));\n","    }\n","}\n"],"metadata":{"id":"KK9SaO2bxSPZ"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["---\n","\n","## 6.2 Generating Documentation\n","\n","**a) Using the `javadoc` tool (command-line)**\n","\n","```bash\n","javadoc -d doc -private JavadocExample.java\n","```\n","- `-d doc` tells javadoc to put the generated HTML files in a directory named `doc`.\n","- `-private` includes private members in the documentation (otherwise they are excluded).\n","\n","---\n","\n","**Exercise**\n","1. Run the following commands:"],"metadata":{"id":"-uxnNtPDxiTx"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["!javadoc -d doc -private JavadocExample.java"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"67L-YDvkyNhN","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1737432126380,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":2926,"user":{"displayName":"Tyler","userId":"06315977947093285888"}},"outputId":"b7dd92be-983b-46da-c940-6a8ee1909bf2"},"executi